Patch Set 5: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

While I have no real objection to this, I also do not understand the utility.  I get how it adds some code coverage to the tests suite but it does not seem to be actually testing any behavior at all.  It seems that all that happens is every call in main is mocked out, and then we verify that the calls were made in that order.  I am having a hard time seeing what regression or bug this will trap.  In other words, how do these tests help us ensure that no future bugs will slip into cache_cleaner?

Patch Set 5:

I have a similar comment in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/46064/.  This test gives us coverage, but what behavior does it test?

also, does this need to depend on 46064?

Patch Set 5: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Same concerns as jbresnah. Seems everything is mocked and we're just verifying the invoking order. So would you mind taking an example to clarify what kind of bug will be caught by this coverage? And it would be nice if a bug can be opened to associate with this patch. Thanks.

Patch Set 5:

As I can see, code in cache_cleaner.py has two goals:
1. Prepare required conditions and run cache cleaner.
2. Catch RuntimeErrors and call system exit with the exception details. 

So to test this module we need two tests. The first one should verify that all conditions are prepared before running the Cleaner. And then it should verify that Cleaner was actually started. The second one should verify that exceptions handling was implemented. As the code was developed without unit tests I only added unit tests missed during development.

What issues they can prevent in future? If a developer refactors the code, adds come preconditions, changes/removes exception handling, due to these unit tests they have to doublecheck, if their changes break some original call sequence.
I mocked all internall calls because it's another logic that is not a point to check in these tests. For example, why do I need to ckeck parsing arguments if I want to verify, if it was called before running cleaner and not after. And so on.
